< Text>
Scottie and his staff were on point this evening.  They immediately greeted us by name (the husband had made reservations) when we walked through the door.  A table had already been set up for us along with two glasses of complimentary champagne (we were celebrating a belated Valentine's Day).  The waitress, and I am so sorry I can't remember her name, was phenomenal.  She was very attentive and polite.  The food was delicious, especially the garlic bread and cordon bleu.  As we we're getting ready to leave after a meal, or waitress was so kind and handed us our leftovers as she opened the door for us. Such a wonderful little restaurant, and a great staff. On a side note, it was wonderful to see the owner inside the restaurant greeting customers, helping at the tables, and also cooking in the kitchen.  Bravo!< /Text>

< text>
Absolutely Satisfied.

The abridged review - great atmosphere, amazing food and excellent service. My husband and I can‚Äôt wait until our next visit! Thank you to Scottie and the wonderful staff you have employed. Truly made our anniversary very special, especially being our first as Brentwood residents!

I have to note, we had our excellent experience all while two new staff members were being trained in the kitchen and two servers had called in sick. Keep reading for the detailed review.. : )

My husband and I are relatively new to Brentwood and heard this was the best place in town for a romantic night out. We were celebrating our 4 year wedding anniversary and were not disappointed in our experience. They note ‚Äòslow service‚Äô on their site, unless you have a time constraint (in which case let them know). We thought the night was wonderful and really let us enjoy each plate as it came.

We had a table right opposite the kitchen and really enjoyed watching all the food be prepared. We were able to watch as such delicious plates were created and sent out. We started with the garlic bread and their caprese salad. Delish! The garlic bread comes with a great dipping sauce too! Then we shared a bowl of the soup de j‚Äôour, cream of asparagus. SOO GOOD. My husband had their steak dish - the veggies were cooked perfectly and the mushroom/red wine sauce/topping to the steak was amazing! I ordered the chicken riesling - soo good! Again, veggies were perfectly cooked and complimented the dish so nicely. I wanted to lick both our plates! We finished our meal with a piece of their cheesecake - HOLY COW - so delicious and light. We were in love. Can‚Äôt wait to visit again!!<//text>

< review>
I'm so sad tonight was such a disappointment. We went a year ago, and it was a 5 star experience. This time, the food was not nearly as good and dinner service was extremely slow. We sat there for 45 mins after we finished our appetizer as waiting for our main dishes to come out.

Last year, I had the escargot appetizer, and it was the most amazing version of escargot I've ever had. This year, it tasted like cleaning fluid and rancid nuts. I had to send it back, and I NEVER send back dishes. It was just inedible.

The duck breast was good and cooked perfectly, but the flavor combinations on the plate were poorly done. The black rice risotto had little flavor. The mushrooms were under cooked and didn't feel like a good part of the dish. And I'm a mega fan of mushroom risotto. But honestly, a frozen bag from Trader Joes tastes better.

Unfortunately, tonight was such a turn off, I don't think we will be going back ever again. I'm so sad, last year was amazing. I have a deep love for French quizine. I don't know if management changed or just the chef, but this was no where near as good as it was a year ago.< /review>

< text>
Jazz music background (and live on Fri or Sat), curated wines (and free tastings) from local vintners and wonderful French-inspired cuisine.  Our meal on July 4th was amazing.  With the one exception of broth for mussels being a bit saltier than we'd like, all the dishes were winners - Chicken Cordon Bleu, Beef/Pork meatloaf, Bone-in pork chop, Duck confit were the entrees.  Sides were delicately prepared and seasoned to match.  Sauces were French-style savory reductions.  Desserts!  Fabulous!  Chocolate Fondant, Creme brulee cheesecake (not sweet - firm, rich, creamy), Fruit tart (warm, crumby, almond background like marzipan).  Not a cheap date, but a top pick for Brentwood.< /text>

<resp>{'time': 1584203279374, 'text': 'Sergey!!! You have been here before Buying used tires. You asked me for a quote for new tires and I‚Äôll give you a quote for two cars your Honda and Toyota. I showed you the tires that we have on the display and you agree on them. After we install them You ask me why are they different brand. I explain to you day before and showed you what you‚Äôre going to get so you paid me in full and we ordered them.\nI did you a favor I called Les Schwab and their price for your Toyota basic tires Starting price installed are $499 Our price from mid brand is $320. Just To be clear you saved money we did not rip you off from your side that was a total lie.\n\nHave a blessed day'}</resp>< text>
Heard good things about Vlad‚Äôs Tires, so tried it for the first time. I did like the service, its fast, and from what I heard - quality service (so far - so good). Dont mind being charged extra for service if they do a good job. Compared to other places that charge $10 per tire, here I was charged $15 per tire on prius and $20 per tire on Honda Odyssey. Most important, I definitely was overcharged for the tires. And when I say overcharged I mean $150 extra at least. I paid with the impression that I was getting Hankook tires (receipt said nothing about what kind of tires im receiving), but upon installation, I found out that that they were Nankang sp-9. Originally, I was quoted $320 for these tires INSTALLED, but wanted something better (and willing to pay more for better tires), so I was quoted a higher price. Turned out I paid $90 (before tax) per tire ($487 total installed) on Odyssey when you can get them for $60-$65... that‚Äôs a big difference from $320. And thats just one car... I asked the owner a few times if he is sure that‚Äôs the right price for these tires and if he charges everyone like this - and he said yes. Well, that was my first experience.

As a follow up to your reply: Les Schwab - you know what you are getting and what you pay for. At your place - you dont know what you pay for.

And no, i never bought used tires from you, inquired - yes. Fixed tires - yes.</text>

< text>
I got the honey/coleslaw/pickle sandwich and it was Huge! The chicken is moist and tender and the flavors of the sandwich were really good together. This originally came with the waffles for bread but after asking they suggested getting the bun to soak up the honey which I think was a great idea. I have had the waffle sandwich before and I believe that the waffles could be better. They're not crispy... I've also had the garlic fries and fresh biscuits with gravy and they are ridiculously tasty! Will definitely visit again.</text>

< Text>
The grilled chicken sandwich used to be delicious, but now is always overcooked since they started using chicken strips instead of chicken breast. I've tried it 5 times just to make sure and it was consistently tough and chewy every time.

Please give us the option to go back to making it the old way before the change! I'd rather it be consistently tender and delicious than have "more chicken" that is overcooked.

I think they changed it to cut costs, but if not I really hope they'll add an option to make it the old way.<//Text>

< review>
Best prices in town bar none! Went online late in the afternoon and submitted my order and an appointment all at the same time for next day service. Tires had to be ordered and were promised the next day even when my specific tires were all backordered from the many tire shops in town. There was another Big Box store, won't mention the name *cough*costcough*üòâ that could get them in 2-5 business days but they were going to cost a bit more. I'll tell you I got a hell of a deal on K02's with alignment! The store manager really took care of me. The guys are professionals and are hard at work. They got me in and out in a little over an hour. Take advantage of their Buy 3 Get 1 Free Tire Promotion! I didn't need anything else serviced from the shop, granted I can do my own brakes and other suspension work. If your looking for great service, deals and friendly professionals come check out the folks here on Rosedale Hwy American Tire Depot! They have a flat screen tv for entertainment, refreshments and a vending machine in the waiting/lobby area. The Air Conditioning works great as well! Stay fresh and cool from this Bakersfield heatwave while you get fast and friendly service at a great deal! Highly recommend.</review>

< review>
For years, I've been to a variety of other salons, and have repeatedly been disappointed. I've had my hair severely burned with perms, color that was way wrong or washed out on the first washing, haircuts that were lopsided or not even close to what I was wanting, and the list goes on. I've brought my son her for 15 years. My husband has come here for 15 years. I tried it several years ago, but when I tried to come back to get the same stylist I was told I couldn't do that. So, I've been all over, until a several months ago. I came back here and gave them a chance with me, again. The stylist was one of, if not the best, I've ever had. She cut my hair perfectly. She colored it the way I wanted it. She understood what I was going for, and how to get my hair there. She was friendly, respectful, efficient, and very skilled. I can make appointments with her, or just walk in. It is wonderful. All staff are friendly, helpful, and knowledgable. They also carry lines of hair care that work. They are not overly costly, as some salons sell. I highly recommend this Salon, especially, Tricia. She rocks.<//review>

<Date>1603862802591</Date>< rating>
5</rating>
<review>I was here on October/ 25/20.
No parking fee, no bathroom, no entrance fee.
It is 4 miles there& back, around 520ft of elevation gain.
The road leading to the lake is very rough and require 4WD.
The trail is 100 % no shade, dirt and dry, very boring hike.
I was lucky, I got a ride from local family.( father and 2 kids),they are very nice people, we payed them for round trip.
The lake is so gorgeous and Mammoth Mountain across the way makes it‚Äôs incredible phenomenon views.
I was walking though those pillars,  they are so unique, some of the columns about 20 ft tall,  with some of them standing as erect as towering pylons,  and sporting ringed apertures approximately a foot apart, another which are warped or leaning at various angles, and some can go all the way back, resemble the petrified remains of dinosaur.
This place could be tourist destination, It is some kind of the beauty that you have to see yourself.</review><pictures>[{'url': < review>
I've driven past Crowley Lake many times, but somehow I can't remember if I've ever gotten down to the water's edge. It's a beautiful lake surrounded by the mighty Sierra Nevada and White mountains. It's a popular fishing spot. I usually prefer to venture out to the lakes at higher elevations. This is a great view as seen from McGee Creek Trailhead.<//review>

5<//Rating>
< review>
The Eastern High Sierra's are where God rested on the Seventh Day. This place is phenomenal! It has everything you could want: Alpine Lakes, forbidding granite mountains, blue-ribbon fishing, sapphire lakes, hiking, diverse & unique landscape, world class skiing, unspoiled wilderness, deep forests, and the cleanest air and water! My favorites are Crowley in the south, Tahoe in the center, and Eagle lake in the north. Go there. Now. Your spirit will be refreshed and and your troubles will be far away.< /review>

<review>as much as I want to support a small local business during this time, this place needs serious sanitation improvements.

1. The guy making our food wasn't wearing a mask or gloves.

2. It also looks like "cleaning their hands" involves wiping them quickly on the same rag (I didn't see water or soap used but I could have missed that).

3. I asked for sanitizer and they apparently didn't have any which I don't care about for my own use, but what does that say about the people making your food?

4. He then made a salad with his bare hands, and then picked up the phone and a pen and wrote down another order, then went back to salad making without washing.

Honestly, not sure if I should be more worried about coronavirus or ecoli.

<user_name>Jeffrey Miller</user_name>< date>
1620772307973<//date>
<rate>5< /rate>< review>
Haven't been to DZ Akins during covid times. Have always enjoyed it in the past.
Went there on Saturday at noon. The place was a zoo and the waiters looked tired.. Our table took awhile to get someone assigned but the host came by to take drink orders and get someone to help us. We weren't in a hurry so and recognize when people are overwhelmed.
I had the Roast Beef and Ortega sandwich with macaroni salad. My mom had a hamburger and brother the Pastrami.  All 3 of us enjoyed the food and the waitress was great and attentive.  She been there a long time as I recognized her from the past and have forgotten her name. They all wore masks and as far as I could see, everyone around us seemed pleased.
DZ Akins is a great place to take mom or a date. It has some really tasty food and is pretty reasonably priced.
Now if I could just remember her name!<//review>

I'm from North Jersey originally and had a hard time finding a deli in San Diego that met my very picky standards. This place was not only the best in San Diego but put most of the delis from back home on notice too. It's a bit pricey but until you see the portions you don't realize you're underpaying for the quality and size of the meals you're getting. My wife takes me out for my birthday each year and I could pick any restaurant I wanted but I always pick DZ Akins. Also since covid is a thing now i feel obligated to say they are doing more than other restaurants to create a safe environment for their patrons and I really appreciate that since I'm in a high risk group.<//text>

We had brunch here and I was very impressed. This is a Jewish deli serving excellent food with very sizable portions. We had 5 star service from a server that's been working there for almost 20 years. I had a sausage and mushroom omelette with Monterrey jack cheese. It was very filling. My order came with potatoes and a muffin. The deli also serves bakery items so if you have a sweet tooth this place is worth checking out. Everyone in our party enjoyed the food. They have a parking lot with free parking. Pay the cashier at the end before leaving. Feel free to leave a like. Cheers!<//text>

<user_name>Sandie Kuhlman<//user_name>< time>
1565652215598</time>
<rating>1<//rating>< Text>
Tuesday, August 6 - My husband and I had lunch here today.  I had the BBQ Treat sandwich with onion rings and he had the Philly Cheese Steak sandwich with fruit.  To begin with our waitress was exceptional!  One of the best we've seen and we eat out a lot.  The food was delicious and made perfectly.  The meat on my sandwich was tender and flavorful, and the BBQ sauce was perfectly tangy.  On the way out we stopped at the bakery and purchased dessert for later..carrot cake cupcake and chocolate custard eclair (mine).  YUM!!  Today I rated it 5 stars...but then we came back the following week...

Monday, August 12 - Last week our lunch was so good (as mentioned above) that I wanted to come back for another BBQ Treat sandwich.  Unfortunately, unlike last week, the service today was terrible and the restaurant was only half full.  It took 15 minutes before someone came over to take our drink orders and then another 10 minutes to get the drinks.  My husband ordered the Mish Mash and it was fine.  When my order finally arrived the meat was tough and chewy and basically uneatable.  The BBQ sauce was bland, tasteless, and had no tang whatsoever.  I don't know why there was such a big difference in taste and quality and service from last week but it was a huge disappointment especially since I was looking forward to it all morning.  Even though I couldn't eat it I hate wasting food so I paid for it and took it home to see if my husband could eat it later.  So, unfortunately, I had to rate it only 1 star.< /Text>

Quintessential diner experience!  Seasoned wait staff and large, open booth seating area gives this place a lot of old-school charm.  Huge menu with daily specials and all day breakfast really ensures something for everyone.  The prices are about what you'd expect from a non-chain diner, but the portions are not disappointing and the quality is outstanding.  On the weekend, get seated before 9am to beat the rush.</Review>

<text>I live a hour north of this restaurant and everytime I visit family (which is often) in San Diego I make sure to stop by, even with the pandemic when everything was closed, we would phone in our order and I will drive by to pick it up. Love, love, love their rare roast beef sandwich on challah (they have both sliced and bun to choose from). My daughter always has their soup and 1/2 a sandwich (6oz of meat so not really 1/2 a sandwich, more like 3/4 sandwich lol). She loves the kreplach soup which is served in a very large, what I would call a pasta bowl. It has chicken broth, noodles and carrots in it. It is a good meal all by itself.  They have a full bakery where I make sure to stop by and get some rugelach cookies for my trip home. They offer tons of ice cream shakes, cakes, pies, cookies, bread, bagels,  rolls and so much more. Before walking out the door, we always stroll through the quaint gift shop located in the restaurant.  I have bought, believe it or not, several silver (real, not plated or whatever) rings for my daughter. They have tons of gifts to chose from though. If you are in the area and would like a true deli style meal, make sure to stop by and try this place out.< /text>< Rate>
5</Rate>

<GmapID>0x80d956f1769222eb:0x8de1ab4c735f7005< /GmapID><response>None< /response>< Text>
Stopped in after a double hike this morning. Shirley had a hankering to eat here this morning. Nice location, quick seating, and great chow. I chose a bacon egg sammich, side fruit cup and a cup of Joe. The roll for the sammich was an egg bread roll I think. Not particularly fond of it with my bacon egg, nothing wrong with it, just old dog, set in my ways, I will come again, just get toasted English muffin, or bagel with my breakfast. Shirley had a pastrami and brisket sammich. Holy moly was it huge! I did not think she could eat it all, clearly learning new things about my Carnivorous gf. Fruit cup was okay.
I will clearly come here again to eat, and try something different.
Come on down folks for great chow at DZ Akins! Parking can be difficult, come early.< /Text>

< rating>

< time>
1578764966515<//time>
<Gmap_id>0x80d956f1769222eb:0x8de1ab4c735f7005</Gmap_id><name>Josh Sanders</name><Pics>None< /Pics>< Text>
This place has no downside. Every aspect of DZ Akins is top of the line. The sandwichs are almost to big to eat. Piles of corned beef and pastrami, heaped onto a slice of rye or sourdough. You could bring half this sandwich home and make two regular size sandwiches out of it. The servers are fast and friendly, and have your meal on the table in minutes. While you wait, there is a crock of pickles on the table with tongs to help yourselves. Your choice of mustard is also on the table. Lots of napkins are provided. No better sandwich could be made. And when you are through eating, pay the cashier and hit the pastry and cookie counter in the entrance. Every kind of cookie, cake, pastry, large cake, tort, ethnic pastry and bread. The also sell fresh made bagels. They also have a meat counter with small to large buys  for parties. They also have a great gift shop with items of quality that you won't find anywhere else. This is not your ordinary restaurant,  this place is a celebration of food and the best of everything that is food. If I died in this place, it would take the undertaker a week to get the smile off my face. Love Love Love DZ Akins.</Text>

< Review>
It was horrible I had a number 62 pastrami on rye with kraut mozzarella an onion ring. The rye bread with so over toasted you could have made diamonds with it to glass. Then in an attempt to soften the over toasted bread or charcoal they drowned it in butter so much to the point that it was Dripping. The butter then overwhelmed of course the flavor of the rye bread the sauerkraut monsterella cheese and the poor cut and skimpy portions pastrami, I ordered onion rings I got six rings that were equally drenched in oil to the fact that you could have run them out and floated a candle wick in the oil. I ordered a soda which was a 24 oz soda is what I received no choice given on the side that cost $3.50 all in all out the door it cost me over $22 for a vat  of grease and a pot of charcoal.

So the truly sad thing about it is. I have eaten there before and was happy, not ecstatic but happy, I probably at that point in time. I would have given them a 3.5 maybe a 4 rating. This time the only reason I'm giving them a one is that the lowest score that Google has available if they had a -5 I would give it to them.</Review>

< Text>
Waitress was a sweetheart but clearly flustered and overworked. She did her best to take care of us but I can't stand when I'm at an establishment and it isn't adequately staffed. On the plus side food was good. Do NOt get the kids Mac n cheese though unless you like overcooked "not Kraft" boxed product lol. My daughter didn't touch it but the waitress kindly removed it from the bill. Lots of treats to choose from  and HUGE portions and we enjoyed our classic diner favorites here. Ice cream could probably be better quality tho... It was a bit runny and melting all over the place by the time it reached our table and didn't have that nice  homemade flavor I like (I'm  not sure of it was or not).  Either way it at least tasted pretty good but I'll aim to come here when it's way less busy and it'll probably be a better experience.<//Text>

<Text>A Great Deli. We are real fans of DZ Akins. Have been going there for about 5 years. This is an old fashioned Deli with photos of local and national celebrities hung on the walls.  (Our young adult children don't like going there because of the often older clientele! Their loss!) This is the type of Deli that serves great sandwiches and dinners. They have a wonderful bakery that has the best rugula.  They have a sandwich of the day that is plenty big enough to make 2 meals. They also have a good choice of soups... Real homemade soup. The sweet and sour cabbage soup is our favorite. Most of the very long last of sandwiches they offer are really good. Try their Ruben! And you can get that with a "seedless rye bread", thank you. The only thing I can't recommend is the Filly Cheesesteak. I just had it today. The long roll it was on was nicely toasted, but had SO many sesame seeds that it almost overwhelmed the sandwich. Then the meat (nice thin slices) was way over cooked and dry. They're didn't seem to be any seasonings on the meat to make it a more interesting taste. So don't get the Wednesday special!   But everything else we have had there is definitely recommended.<//Text>< gmap_id>

<Review>I'm from the East coast where Jewish delis are very plentiful, so I may be a bit biased here. I enjoyed my experience but I found the food to only be average. My sandwich bread was actually kind of small, which required the meat to be stacked much higher than necessary. Deli's back east stack meat high, but on large portions of bread!  The turkey was dry, the corned beef only fine and overall the sandwich was lacking flavor.  Could have used a creamier coleslaw or more Russian dressing to really help it out.

Onions rings were perfect and the service and staff were really great!  Everyone was super friendly and they had plenty of people working to help out.

I will definitely go back because it fills a deli void in my stomach, but it's more like a pale echo of a good deli back east.< /Review>< GmapID>

Great Jewish food, but I was surprised to see something so not kosher. So if you're looking for great Jewish good this is the place, but if you want kosher food this is not a place to go.< /Text>

< review>
It's been ages since I've visited DZ Akins.  The food is great and the portions large.  I had the brisket dip with potato salad.  And the pickle jar is always a hit.  At $16.95 it was a steep price.  Of course you can't leave there without hitting the dessert counter.  A carrot cake cupcake, chocolate on chocolate cupcake, cherry turnover, and blueberry scone set me back $18.50.  Prices rather high so it'll have to be a special occasion before I'll be back.< /review>

<Review>Homey, cozy, what i can assume to be traditional style old fashioned jewish cuisine. The wide variety of pastrami sandwich selections, self serve from the pot kosher pickles, body warming and filling matzo ball soup, daily specials. You need to come back and come back often to be able to try everything on this gigantic menu. After your meal polish it off with either a traditional Jewish dessert or what i like to do, get a selection of kosher pastries from their bakery our front. 5< /rating>
< text>
If you grew up somewhere on the eastern seaboard and miss 'real' deli food, DZ Akin's is your best bet in the greater San Diego area. While there are many that claim to be a deli, there is nowhere else in town that even comes close to fulfilling that promise. This includes the quirky sense of humor, prominent pickle jars on each table, super-extensive menu, and numerous ethnic dishes.  They can get extremely busy, so expect to wait at dinnertime. Make sure to stop in the bakery afterward for dessert..</text>

<user>116055486866505545366< /user>< name>
Pablo Ben</name>
<date>1549605037113< /date>< Rate>
4</Rate>
<Text>Traditional Jewish Deli, New York style.
This is an old traditional spot in San Diego, and one of the few places in town where you can get this cuisine.
Some dishes are awesome, others not so much. Overall quality is good.
Joining their email list will allows you to go when they serve specials, which are often great, especially lamb, oxtail soup, and split peas soup.
They excell at making: chopped liver (which they make themselves rather than buy), kishka, onion rolls (also baked there), knish, meatloaf, and in all their pastries.
This is also a good place for a quality but budget breakfast, as they have very affordable deals in the morning.
The most interesting aspect of the restaurant is the place itself, full of memories, painted walls with funny secrets you can discover if you pay attention, and lots of framed jokes.
Service is one of their strengths. They are very friendly and professional and you usually get your meal quickly. Refills come without even asking.
Parking is always easy, they have a huge lot that never fills up.< /Text>< pics>
None</pics>

< review>
I LOVE this place. From their hamburgers to their kreplach soup and their MASSIVE salads. (If it's just you eating... get the half salad, trust me) Their food is always great and you're always able to see the owners, they're there all the time. Not something you see at most places.
The waitresses are amazing, how anyone can remember EVERYTHING on those menus is beyond me, and incredibly impressive. The staff in general is great, they get what you need and get you on your way quick. This place gets busy, so it helps if you're a seasoned vet like me with their menu, if not and you don't like a crowd, check out their menu online before you order to-go.
Even if you don't think you'll like this place, try it. It'll soon be on your short list to go every time.< /review>

None< /Response>
< Text>
Looking for good NY deli?  This is not it.  Had matzo ball soup and sandwich combo.  The soup was just OK it was rich but i had better ones before.  The sandwich was a total disaster.  It was pastrami half sandwich on two peaces of stale bread with nothing else in it.   The bread was so dry and stale  and other than the pickles they did not provide any mayo or anything until we asked.  Pastrami tasted good but again I ordered a sandwich and as a whole it sucked  since it was hard to eat.  Given the traffic here I would think they would have the freshest bread and al of us got stale bread.    This place is supposed to have some of the best sandwiches but this was really disappointing.   My friends were disappointed as well.  They went to Jewish deli in LA and were raving about it so wanted to come here and check this one out since they live nearby. Total let down.  The service was pretty good considering how busy it was.< /Text>

<Text>I've been coming here for a few years on and off and the quality is consistent. Many of the servers have been there for years and are friendly. Service is usually very good, when it does get busy it can be just okay.

The menu is pretty large so it can be a hunt if you're not sure what you want. I usually come for breakfast,  getting the breakfast special, which is eggs, bacon/sausage, and pancakes. It's a great deal on a weekday. The food can be somewhat oily or greasy depending on what you get, but it's usually made well and just right. <rate>5<//rate>< Review>
Is this place filled with old people? Yes. Is there somehow always a wait? Yes. Does the parking here increase your risk of a heart attack? Yes, but so does the delicious food.  This is an actual old school diner that I hope never changed.  Its the only place that your grandma will eat and you're secretly fine with it.  No matter what you're craving you can find it on the menu that seems to get bigger every time you're there.  I'd recommend trying everything once but don't want you to get gout. After a late lunch that grandma kept calling dinner, you can go to the bakery/deli area and order a cream puff the size of your head.  Meanwhile your mom buys some smoked brisket and rye bread for sandwhices when you regain consciousness from your food coma.< /Review>

If you're looking for satisfying comfort food, DZ Akins will hit the spot. I would suggest coming for their early bird dinner special. It's a really good deal. Otherwise, this place can be pricey. The menu is extensive so it's tough to choose. My faves inc: matzo ball soup, pastrami Reuben, meatloaf, and mushroom chicken. The portions are hearty so you'll probably leave with leftovers. The service is friendly. As an added bonus, all you can eat pickles from the jar on your table. I like to eat mine with spicy sweet mustard.</text>

< Text>
So you like the New York deli experience? You can't do worse than visit this San Diego institution. They've got everything from corned beef and pastrami to matzo ball soup to blintzes to kasha to knishes and so much more.

I currently live in a place where this kind of food isn't available, and whenever I can make it to Southern California, I always try to make sure I get down to this restaurant for my fix. I always get what they refer to as a, Ted, Leitner special: corned beef, pastrami, and Swiss on rye bread with Russian dressing. It's bliss.

Before leaving, don't forget to browse their bakery for some goodies to go.</Text>

< user>
113148921595557385171</user>
<GmapID>0x80d956f1769222eb:0x8de1ab4c735f7005< /GmapID>< review>
Love love this place! Man, San Diego really does have some great restaurants, and this is one of them!

Plenty of breakfast items to choose from, lots of sandwiches and soups that are always delicious and fresh. Don't even get me started on the cookies and cakes and yummy desserts that are right up front in the glass case. Every time I go there I seriously have to leave with a bag of goodies.

Most of the staff has worked there for years, and they are very fast and friendly. It is a little bit on the pricey side, but they do give large portions so you will have food to take home for the most part. Parking can be a little bit tricky if you go during busy times, but it's definitely worth it.<//review>

1514538301235</date>

< text>
I've been dining at DZ Akins for over 20 years now and I'm happy to report that it is still the best authentic Jewish deli in San Diego! There are others that try like Milton's and Samson's but DZ Akins is the real deal!

Also the manager is a super nice fellow named Elan who makes sure everything runs smoothly and is great! Love their fresh baked Breads and bakery items as well as their deli sandwiches and soups! Don't waste your time on the other delis in town if you want a great meal go here! I usually order the soup and mini sandwich which sounds like a small meal but is actually a very large bowl of any of their soups served with what is essentially a normal sized sandwich that they refer to as a half sandwich. Sure to satisfy!</text>

My only bad experience happened when I politely complained at the cash register that $3.25 was too much to charge for a cup of coffee. 0x80d956f1769222eb:0x8de1ab4c735f7005< /gmap_id>
< user>
117306427833891633543< /user>
< review>
This place used to be great. The food was good and so was the service.

It has gone down hill. The food does not taste fresh, and most of the staff look like they would rather be somwhere else.

The omelet I ordered today was supposed to come with cheese, avocado and mushrooms--and it did--but it also came with an unpleasant odor. Those mushrooms were not fresh, and mushrooms need to be fresh or they ruin the entire dish.

The mocha tasted like the chocolate milk you make from Hershey's chocolate syrup. It wasn't bad. It just wasn't great.

The blintzes we got were not good either. We could not taste the filling and the blintzes tasted like they were fried in rancid oil.

Oh, the waitress argued with me about the mushrooms.

Anyway, this place costs substantially more than most other places that serve breakfast. In the past, the quality of the food made up for this.I don't know why people keep coming here.

That's another sign that this place has gone down hill. D.Z. Akins should have been packed at the time we went. There should have been a line out the door, but the place had at least a third of it's tables empty.

I suspect they have lost many of their repeat customers, and it is not hard to see why. As it is right now, this place sucks.

I'm sorry if this offends you. I used to love this place too.</review>

< text>
I have eaten at D.Z. Akins  for over 30 years and have received excellent food with outstanding service, until now.  While eating a delicious lunch with 2 friends our server dropped a few glasses and plates while emptying our table. The water and food spilled on our table and on our friend's  business proposal papers.

Our server and a helper quickly did a fast but not thorough wiping of the table.  Our server left and her helper tossed us some napkins to clean the table ourselves.  The server and her helper then left abruptly.

Our server did not apologize for her blunder, and a few minutes later delivered our 3 bills with only briskly saying here are your bills.

We were pleasant and did not complain, but our server could have apologized and also have helped us clean our table.  D.Z. Akins has wonderful servers, but this lady was not one.</text>

< Name>
Steven Freshour<//Name>
<Date>1427643324827</Date>< rate>
4< /rate>
< review>
I remember always coming here during my college days to get a cheese steak sandwich.  That's all I ever ordered back then.  Well, I returned to San Diego a few weeks back and noticed this place had a groupon option so my bf and I returned.  During our stay in SD, we ate here three mornings in a row.  We were looking for a breakfast joint that could accommodate our dietary restrictions.

We both really enjoyed their lox and onion scrambled eggs.  Instead of potatoes or fruit, we requested the cottage cheese (which tasted really fresh).  I cheated and ate their muffins.  Banana nut muffin, you always get me!

My last return here, I decided to really cheat.  I ordered their matzo ball soup (because I love matzo ball soup and everyone raves about it here), had corned beef hash and my bf ordered their rueben sandwich (half pastrami and half corned beef)  Our lucky day, it was the sandwich special.

It all tasted great!  The matzo ball soup had more carrots than I cared for.  The corn beef hash, yum.  The Reuben sandwich though...especially yum!  We had that with three bean salad.  As a person who usually hates three bean salads, the one here was tasty!  If you like vinegar which I love.

Also, can't forget the pickles!

We also got some stuff from the bakery.  The items that stood out for me was the rolled baklava.  Love me some pistachio baklava.

Wait staff was extremely attentive and courteous.  I would definitely return.< /review>

None<//Pics>

<user_id>111932751044926982478< /user_id><username>Deirdre Bramberg<//username><Time>1594931102976<//Time><Rate>5< /Rate><review>Best bakery</review><pics>None</pics>< response>

<gmapID>0x80d956f1769222eb:0x8de1ab4c735f7005</gmapID></record></dataset><record>
<pictures>None<//pictures><time>1528535282601< /time>< Review>
Came out of the bakery with a good week of supplies in diverse bagels, pastries and bread....everything looked delicious.
What I love about their pastry shop /bakery is that everything looks good but without looking anything but artisanal,  it doesn't look fake/artificial...no over the top too colorful cupcakes or sprinkles....no this is the real deal!
And did I tell you about the cream cheese I got....man!I'm never eating industrial cream cheese again....it changed my life.
About the restaurant,  sure the decor is a bit old fashion but hey....it s part of the charm. The food was absolutely great.... and it is sooooo authentic! We went home with a box and we were glad to be able to enjoy it again.I even liked the pickles and god knows I'm not a fan...the bananasplit was absolutely  huge!!the fudge was delicious!
I love that most of their servers seem to be 40-60 years old ladys, they are super warm and professional.
The place is as big as the portions....gigantic....and just as warm and njce as the servers.
Definitely asking my man to take me back!!< /Review>

<user>109730518093248606041</user><username>N Russell</username><Date>1533770316656<//Date><Rate>4</Rate>< Text>
I've been living in San Diego before DZ Akins existed. I remember how they began on one end of the building and then slowly took over the Potpourri Art Store and then the entire building. The food is very good and so are the pastries but one thing... there has always been a lingering presence in the air of a kind of arrogance (if you will). Difficult to describe but it is as if the people who work there at the cashiers desk always seem to have a certain something going on as if they have (one-up on you in some way or other). Always nice and pleasant but with an undercurrent that commands a certain type of respect for the insanely high prices they have always charged for all their items. In other words... don't even think about arguing with us about our prices because we ain't coming down!  I've been to Jewish Deli's in New Jersey, New York City and in Miami, FL and they are all pretty much similar to the D Z Akins establishment. Some people are known for gauging the public when it comes to over charging them. It's a known fact. They always have the best to offer but I think that with the very (high) volume that they have (always) had... there is (no) need to charge people such ridiculously high prices for a simple lunch. Yes, you do get a huge amount of whatever in your sandwich but not $20 some odd dollars worth when you ad a drink and a side of potato salad or whatever. It's just way too much to have to pay. That's why I haven't dined there in several years. The owner used to park his Rolls Royce right smack dab in front of the place so all the patrons could see it. Customers would then sit there and ponder why can't this guy drive a toyota and charge us all much less for our sandwich? It's that rubbing his wealth (at our expense) in our faces that was a turn-off. Otherwise, I'd say if you happened to have won the Powerball recently... that is about the only way you could afford to dine there without it leaving you feel as though you were put through a financial hurricane when you got the bill. WHAT? $70 bucks just for lunch for two people? They must be out of their minds. It's just plain old TOO MUCH. That is the kind of money you'd expect to pay to dine at Jakes by the Sea in Del Mar or at George's at the Cove in La Jolla... not in a tiny track mall environment.<//Text>

< review>
This Jewish Deli/Restaurant is a gem of San Diego. You feel like you're in New York City when you go in there. The pastrami on rye is great. I love the corned beef hash and eggs. On the weekends they have Bialys. Sucha treat. And the bakery. Fresh cookies and cakes, breads, hallahs, bagels. We love the coconut macaroons (gluten-free).<//review>

<review>Coffee is awful, but everything else is really flavorful and well done!

5 stars for an excellent bakery selection. I especially like the chocolate brownies and the poppy seed danish. I order things to go and then go home and make my own coffee to enjoy with bakery treats!

Also fantastic - the bagels! Onion bread is also a fine, egg-based (?) bread, mmm

Deli has a fresh selection of pickled herring, whitefish salad, and coleslaw (not too creamy just how I like it!). Order it to go with some bagels and you have a healthy, delicious meal! Great for snacks if you want wine time with your laughing pack of gfs.

Bakery and deli, mmm..</review>< Pics>

Best Deli west of the Mississippi. Also great bakery.</Text>

<Gmap_id>0x80d956f1769222eb:0x8de1ab4c735f7005< /Gmap_id></record></dataset><record>
<UserId.>115802051008320845898</UserId.><user_name>charles chiles<//user_name><Date>1507997445305<//Date><rate>5<//rate>< review>
D.Z.Akin's is one of the best delicatessens in San Diego County. The restaurant was brought together by a couple who came to San Diego from Los Angeles ; the idea was that San Diego needed a good deli and after years of hard work, the deam came to fruition.The staff is very professional and extremely friendly and last time that I was there my waitress was there whenever I needed a refill on my tea or just to check to see how I was doing.
Akin's serves over twenty-five different types of kosher sandwiches; using two meat and cheese combinations.
They serve a four meat and cheese special that will set you back about twenty- five dollars however, you may need a 'doggie bag.'
Each sandwich comes with a choice of either a regular salad, a homemade potato salad, or a delicious three bean salad; there are plenty of side dishes to complete your meal - I suggest the fried onion rings. And don't forget the tasty Jewish dill pickles; they are compimentary, as well as different mustards too.
I tried the "Philly steak and provolone cheese sandwich on a hot French roll" and it was awesome! I also ordered a glass of dark tea - refills were complementary; their tea is a good quality tea.
D.Z.AKIN'S also serves large dinners and other kosher foods that all have that special Jewish flair. One may request special alternatives however, substitutions are usually not approved. The bakery in the front of the store sells awesome pastries; I liked the vanilla creme chocolate eclairs ; they are so big that it takes two days to eat just one. Their "creme puff" was huge whipped creme confection, filled with thick vanilla creme.The cookies are sweet and everything is baked on the premises.
Their milk shakes are a "retro" 50's style that are thick and creamy, topped with a towering swirl of real home made whipped cream and a marichino cherry - last time I was there I had a Kuahuala chocolate delight however, unless I had a friend who offered to treat : I should have learned that lesson long ago; that those who give to freely never get anything in return; it's a lesson that everyone should learn and the younger you learn it the wiser and perhaps the wealthier you may be. God never bestows riches upon people who ask Him.
Their is also a very well stocked kosher meat area where one can purchase various sliced meats to create their own smorgasbord for a small intimate get-to-together, as well as a made to order catering service.
The inside of D.Z.Akin deli sports a large   collection of black and white photographs - some colour ones too - of immemorial celebrities, as well as a few of the newer movie stars and a number of world renowned people too; it's a step back in time for those of us who are were living during the time before producers started relying on blue and green screens, computer generated animatronics and "fake" props/images to create realistic scenarios - to fool the ignorant masses.The results have still been fantastic, creating movies where the audience becomes part of the scene itself, especially in 3-D.
The inside of the deli has also been painted with beautiful scenes of D.Z.Akin's everyday life scenes that echo the soul of this deli; paintings so well done that they seem to also have that 3-D effect on the eyes, especially if you look at them for long enough...
D.Z. Akin's also has a guaint little souvenir shoppe
in the front of their store where they sell really nice cards - that commemorate all Jewish holidays as well as any gentile related holidays, such as Christmas, Thanksgiving, etc; there are some beautiful figurines that are relatively inexpensive; I purchased several neat little cat statuettes to add to my collection of animal likenesses and with Halloween just around the corner, there are all kinds of neat and inexpensive little gifts that are less than $10.
There is plenty of parking and one can hook up with The San Diego Trolley Green Line from any other trolley line ,as well as many transit busses to easily reach D.Z.Akin's.</review>

< user>
103124858800019566456</user>
<Pics>None< /Pics>< review>
Don't get me wrong... our family loves DZ and has been going for a LONG time!  But lately it's been "hit or miss".. there is a lack of consistency across dishes and across visits.

The ginormous sandwiches are BOMB diggity.. corned beef and pastrami are delightful... although, I always get chopped liver and/or liverwurst.  Either way, awesome!  I also enjoy the table-side, homemade pickles.. and choices of mustard.  My mom and I frequently get the half-sandwich and soup special.  The Borscht is refreshing on a hot day!

They also have a breakfast special on weekdays from 7am to 11am which consists of Two Large Buttermilk Hotcakes, Two Eggs, Two Strips of Bacon or Two Links of Sausage for $3.99... and they do an early bird dinner special from 4-6pm.

Like I said, we love DZ... but, at times, the bread has been rubbery... the food cold.. the waitress without enthusiasm... one time the waitress even exclaimed "that's not my favorite" after a nearby patron made her order... shouldn't you sell the food you serve?  Not bash it?  And one time we were asked to move by some strange lady who never introduced herself... then, when we didn't, she came back to explain that she was the owner and needed our table.  Should have said that the first time!

So... basically.. if you're going to DZ Akins, go Jewish fare and/or eat a ginormous, double decker sandwich!  Oh yeah.. and don't forget to grab some bakery goods on the way out!  Well worth the price!<//review>

<review>Well, i write this with such sadness. I have been going to DZ Akin's for 16 years, the "Manager" Debra, who has in my opinion been a very friendly manager. I was a GM of a restaurant for nearly 30 years give or take. I have a couple of things to address after being a a loyal customer as i have said 16 years. 7 weeks ago i had the lower third of my spine fused, major surgery, When i finaIy felt able i went to have my favorite Friday Fish and chips( PS: I move from England 33 years ago) Debra the manager even though i'm struggling with my walker, takes us past several empty tables and sits us in the very back, you know where the bathrooms are. I said gee with my walker you couldn't seat us a little closer to the door where i m parked in the handicapped parking spot. (her reply) "well, i don't know how bad your condition is"!!!!  With the surgery i recently got put on a very strict diet for medical reasons complications, so continued going each Friday for my fish and chips ( a little bit of home) every week the waitresses are awesome and sub a salad for the fries as i can no longer have fries to my horror.
"BAM"
Last Night Friday August 5th sat down asked my waitress so bored of salad and coleslaw can i get baked beans and cottage cheese, no problem.
Our waitress comes back,"I am so sorry NO substitutions on the fish and chips" i said thats not possible have substituted for the past two months since i was told no more potatoes. Then Debra, the manager comes over and repeats, yes, no substitutions. i explained to her everything i cant eat potatoes, and they have always substituted, i would be happy just give me one side instead of two. NO!
She then had the nerve to my discuss to say point out the waitresses that have substituted because they shouldn't be. I said NO i am not going to let you attack them the way you are me for giving me substitutions. (My Partner said" better idea, instead of asking to point out your staff just tell everyone at the next staff meeting.) She looked at me and said give me one name and i'll give you one side..............
ONLY because of the medication i was so drugged on did i stay.
Alas i will never be back at DZ akin's again, i want to thank all the wonderful waitress that have taken care of us over the 16years.
But, Debra, you have no business being a manager of any restaurant at all. I never would or did i treat a customer the way you treated us last night. If i was the owner "I WOULD FIRE YOU"
i am posting this on all social media and forwarding a printed copy to your store owner. I have never had to write such a review of any where in such a bad way.
I did not want to give any stars
Keith Willis

<Time>1347342774276<//Time>< rating>
5</rating>
< Text>
The menu is equisite. Something to excite the most finciky of palette's. The service is impeccable. NOT over attentive,they return to your table when you require their service without signaling or voice commands. One of the finest water/waitress staff's in San Diego.I tip my hat to this hidden culinary jewel. I seen reviews of "over-priced" sandwich's. Nonsense..! The sandwich's are worth every penny. From the bread to the contents in between are of the highest quality...Hands down..!
If I had to choose from 'turf-n-surf' or a DZ Akins snadwich I would choose the latter.You'll most likely need a to-go-box for the DZ choice over the turf-n-surf meal from your fav restaurant..
This place is good,and deserves a try. Many comfort foods on the menu.  (Thanx Beckah for gettin me hooked on their Reubin-doin the remodel)</Text>

<Name>DeDe O<//Name><review>This place is a mixed bag. My family moved here right when the pandemic started so we just recently were able to dine-in. We love ordering bagels to-go. This might be the first and last time we visit in person though.

The bakery is great for take-out; bagels are superb! The sit down experience at breakfast was very different. The server was nice but not very attentive. Whizzed by a couple of times, and failed to notice I didn‚Äôt eat my food at all because it was frankly inedible. That‚Äôs partly on me; it was something new to me but also, it was totally flavorless (like, zero seasoning) and cold when it came out. Maybe that‚Äôs normal? IDK. Some people probably like that. It is baffling the server didn‚Äôt seem to care or notice an entire plate of food was untouched. I could have asked for something else or a refund but I figured she‚Äôd offer a solution. Nope.

My parents food seemed fine but definitely overpriced. And $3.50 for a cup of coffee?! I wish I had paid attention to the price before hand. I have never heard of a restaurant charging more than $3 for regular ol‚Äô joe.

No one asked to refresh our water. We only got offered a coffee refill once. I‚Äôve worked in several restaurants myself and this place wasn‚Äôt busy enough to justify the lack of attention.
And  2/3 water cups were dirty. I know dishes get ‚Äúsanitized‚Äù but there was food and OJ ‚Äúbaked‚Äù (for lack of a better description) into the cheap plastic cups.

Last but not least, it took until literally the very end for any plates, etc. to get cleared.

We will come back for bagels and pastries, but dining in is unlikely. I hope others get better food and service than we did.<//review></record>
